stylometry:
Interger programming models have 3 main reasons for being difficult to solve.
	1. No corner points exist in the data as with simpler models
	2. For every decision variable, 2 possible solutions become availible
	3. IP uses an entirely different algorithm for solving models called branch and bound
		This algorithm takes the first set of possible solutions, finds the best in that group and cuts off the other that aren't as optimal, follows the best solutions to the next set of possible solutions, finds the best in that group and cuts off the other, and so on until all possible solutions following that branch have been explored leaving you with the best possible solution of all possible. (the global maximum as opposed to the local maximum found by other algorithms)

In excel its important to note that IP models are differentiated by having changing cells with the constraint of only containing integers, and often even narrowed down to binary. Binary constraints are useful when dealing with problems like trans-shipment with warehouses)
